Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/announces
Object: Relates a written statement work to a thing which the statement announces. A written statement may announce more than one thing.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/House
Object: The holding of a position by a person, including the time period for which this was the case. For example, Philip Hammond holding the position of Foreign Secretary between two dates.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/CorrectedThing
Object: A thing being corrected by the making of a written statement to Parliament, for example: a preceding written statement or a written answer.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/madeBy
Object: Relates a written statement expression to the incumbency of the person making the statement, for example: an incumbency in a ministerial position or an incumbency as Speaker or Lord Speaker.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/follows
Object: Relates a written statement work to the written statement work it follows, for example: a written statement announcing the publication of a review follows a written statement announcing that review.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/madeInHouse
Object: Relates a written statement expression to the House in which the written statement is made.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/Session
Object: A period during which Parliament is able to conduct business on days of its choosing. A session is within a Parliament period. The first session of a Parliament begins on the same day as the Parliament period and ends on a day named in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the Parliament period begin and end on dates named in subsequent prorogation proclamations. The final session of a Parliament ends either with prorogation followed by dissolution or with dissolution. Session periods are the same for both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/madeOn
Object: Relates a written statement expression to the date on which that expression was made.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/corrects
Object: Relates a written statement work to the thing it corrects.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/WrittenStatementWork
Object: A written statement made to Parliament as realised in an expression made to a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/Incumbency
Object: The holding of a position by a person, including the time period for which this was the case. For example, Philip Hammond holding the position of Foreign Secretary between two dates.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/expressionOf
Object: Relates a written statement expression to the written statement work realised by that expression. A written statement work has one written statement expression when a statement is made to one House. A written statement work has two written statement expressions when a statement is made to both Houses. A written statement expression realises one written statement work.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/WrittenStatementExpression
Object: The expression of a written statement as made to a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/refersToDocument
Object: Relates a written statement work to a document to which the statement refers. A written statement may refer to more than one document.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/AnnouncedThing
Object: A thing being announced by the making of a written statement to Parliament, for example: the laying of a paper.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/title
Object: Relates a written statement expression to the title of that expression.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/LibraryDeposit
Object: A paper or set of papers placed by a Minister, or the Speaker, or the Lord Speaker, in the Library of either House. Usually deposits are made into both Libraries but sometimes only one.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/inSession
Object: Relates a written statement work to the session that statement is made in.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/uin
Object: Relates a written statement expression to the UIN of that expression. A UIN is an alphanumeric identifier.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/statementText
Object: Relates a written statement expression to the text of that expression.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/
Object: A model describing written statements made to Parliament as works and expressions of those works.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/written-statement/refersToLibraryDeposit
Object: Relates a written statement work to a library deposit.
